 <sect3 id="sec.prep.powerlinux.powerkvm.template">
  <title>Creating a &sls; Template with Kimchi</title>
  <para>
   Templates are the installation source for &powerkvm; guests.
  </para>

  <procedure>
   <title>Creating a Template with Kimchi</title>
   <step>
    <para>
     In the Web browser, enter the URL of the &powerlinux; server where
     &powerkvm; is running, for example
     <literal>https://<replaceable>powerlinux_ip</replaceable>:8001</literal>
     (replace <replaceable>powerlinux_ip</replaceable> with the IP
     address of your system).
    </para>
   </step>
   <step>
    <para>
     Click the <guimenu>Templates</guimenu> tab to activate the
     <guimenu>Templates</guimenu> page.
    </para>
   </step>
   <step>
    <para>
     Click the green plus sign (<guimenu>+</guimenu>) to create the
     &sls; template.
    </para>
    <para>
     Provide either a local or a remote ISO image of &sls;.
    </para>
    <para>
     Check <guimenu>I want to use a specific ISO file</guimenu>, and
     specify the path to the file of the ISO image.
    </para>
   </step>
   <step>
    <para>
     To configure the newly created template, click
     <menuchoice><guimenu>Actions</guimenu><guimenu>Edit</guimenu></menuchoice>,
     and change the default values as required by your workload.
    </para>
   <informalfigure>
    <mediaobject>
    <imageobject role="fo">
     <imagedata fileref="kimchi_create_template.png" width="50%"/>
    </imageobject>
    <imageobject role="html">
     <imagedata fileref="kimchi_create_template.png" width="50%"/>
    </imageobject>
    </mediaobject>
   </informalfigure>
   </step>
  </procedure>
  <para>
   For more information, see <quote>Setting up a template using
   Kimchi</quote> on <ulink url="http://www-01.ibm.com/support/knowledgecenter/linuxonibm/liabp/liabpkimchitemplate.htm"/>.
  </para>
 </sect3>
 <sect3 id="sec.prep.powerlinux.powerkvm.install">
  <title>Installing &sls; as a Guest with Kimchi</title>
  <para/>
  <procedure>
   <step>
    <para>
     In the Web browser, enter the URL of the &powerlinux; server where
     &powerkvm; is running, for example
     <literal>https://<replaceable>powerlinux_ip</replaceable>:8001</literal>
     (replace <replaceable>powerlinux_ip</replaceable> with the IP
     address of your system).
    </para>
   </step>
   <step>
    <para>
     Click the <guimenu>Guests</guimenu> tab to activate the
     <guimenu>Guests</guimenu> page.
    </para>
   </step>
   <step>
    <para>
     Click the green plus sign (<guimenu>+</guimenu>) to create the &sls; guest.
    </para>
   </step>
   <step>
    <para>
     Enter a <guimenu>Virtual Machine Name</guimenu> for the &sls; guest.
    </para>
    <para>
     Choose the &sls; template created in <xref
     linkend="sec.prep.powerlinux.powerkvm.template"/> and click
     <guimenu>Create</guimenu>.
    </para>
   <informalfigure>
    <mediaobject>
    <imageobject role="fo">
     <imagedata fileref="kimchi_create_guest.png" width="70%"/>
    </imageobject>
    <imageobject role="html">
     <imagedata fileref="kimchi_create_guest.png" width="70%"/>
    </imageobject>
    </mediaobject>
   </informalfigure>
   <para>
    The &sls; guest is created and ready to be started.
   </para>
   </step>
   <step>
    <para>
     Click the red power button to start the &sls; guest.
     Alternatively, select <guimenu>Start</guimenu> from the
     <guimenu>Actions</guimenu> pull-down button.
    </para>
   </step>
   <step>
    <para>
     Click 
     <menuchoice>
     <guimenu>Actions</guimenu><guimenu>Connect</guimenu>
     </menuchoice>, and connect your VNC viewer to the installation process as
     outlined in <xref
     linkend="sec.deployment.remoteinst.monitor.vnc.connect"/>.
    </para>
   </step>
  </procedure>

  <para>
   Now you can continue with the default installation via VNC.
  </para>
 </sect3>

 <sect3 id="sec.prep.powerlinux.powerkvm.install.virt-install">
  <title>Installing &sls; as a Guest with
  <command>virt-install</command></title>

  <para>
   Alternatively, use the <command>virt-install</command> command line
   tool, if you need to install multiple virtual machines on IBM
   &powerlinux; Server systems.  <command>virt-install</command> allows
   many installation scenarios; in the following a remote installation
   scenario via VNC and PXE boot is outlined.
   For more information about <command>virt-install</command>, see
   <xref linkend="sec.libvirt.inst.virt-install"/>.
  </para>

  <para>
   Prepare a repository with the installation sources and PXE boot
   enabled target system as described in <xref
   linkend="sec.deployment.remoteinst.scenario.vncpxe"/>.
  </para>

  <para>
   On the command line, enter something similar as follows (adjust the
   options according to your needs and matching your hardware):
  </para>
  <!-- 52:54:00:d7:4f:af -->
  <screen
>virt-install --name server_sle12 --memory 4096 --vcpus=2 --pxe \
--graphics vnc --os-variant sles11 \
--disk pool=default,size=3000,format=qcow2,allocation=1G,bus=virtio \
-w mac=<replaceable>mac_address</replaceable>,model=spapr-vlan</screen>
  <para>
   It will use VNC graphics, and it will automatically launch the
   graphical client.
  </para>
 </sect3>
